		<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
			<head>Biographical History</head>
			<p>Minna Citron (1896-1991) was an American painter and printmaker.</p>
		</bioghist>
		
		<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
			<head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
			<p>The <emph render="bold">Minna Citron Papers</emph> encompasses the correspondence, artwork,
				writings and memorabilia of the American painter and graphic artist (1896-1991).
				Although revealing little of her personal life, the collection documents Citron's
				artistic career from the 1930s through the mid-sixties. </p><p>Correspondence includes incoming and outgoing business letters, a few from the 1940s followed by a gap during the 1950s. Resuming in 1961 and continuing through 1965, the Correspondence focuses on Minna Citron's associations with art galleries (Ferdinand Roten Galleries, Inc., Aspen Art Gallery), educational institutions (Elmira College), museums (Whitney Museum of American Art, Roanoke Fine Arts Center), professional organizations (American Color Print Society, American Federation of Arts) and public libraries which sponsored her lectures or held exhibitions of her work.

</p><p>Artwork includes an original etching for a bookplate, a partial inventory of Minna Citron's paintings and graphics, and black-and-white photographs of her work. Arranged by title, Writings feature manuscript essays and speeches as well as two articles, "Communication Between Spectator and Artist" (<emph render="italic">College Art Journal</emph>, Winter 1955), and: "The Uncharted Course" (<emph render="italic">Impression</emph>, Fall 1958).

</p><p>Memorabilia contains awards, personal photographs, printed material, publicity, and reviews and comments about Minna Citron's work. Printed material includes clippings (1932-1965), exhibition catalogs (1930s-1960s) and posters for Minna Citron's one-woman and group shows.</p>
		</scopecontent>
